<div id="main_content">
	<h2>New UCF Mentoring and Leadership Program Aims to Keep Minority Students in School</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">Feb. 13, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:ppates@mail.ucf.edu">Patricia Pates</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6957</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.bfsa-ucf.org">Black Faculty and Staff Association </a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Research shows that mentoring helps students succeed in school. It is especially important for minority students who dont have as many role models in higher education, said Patricia Pates, a director in the Student Development and Enrollment Services division at the University of Central Florida.</p><p>Thats why the Black Faculty and Staff Association has sponsored an annual mentoring breakfast for the past 12 years, said Pates, president of the association at UCF. The breakfast showcases many mentoring programs on campus, including peer mentoring, RAMP, McNair and Freshman Friends. During this years breakfast on Thursday, Feb. 15, the group also will kick off a new program sponsored by the association and the universitys Office of Diversity Initiatives. </p><p>The Legacy Program targets second- through fourth-year college students and is an effort to increase retention and graduation rates, develop leadership skills and assist students in reaching their personal, academic and career goals. The program is open to all underrepresented minority students. </p><p>We tend to lose minority students during the junior year, so the focus of this program is on the last three years of college, Pates said. Our mentors will be connecting students to the campus and community network that can help them succeed.</p><p>Guests at the breakfast will provide students information and access to mentors in fields such as finance and business. Legacy representatives are inviting those who want to be mentors or enroll in the mentoring program to attend. </p><p>Students who sign up for the Legacy Program will receive a free ticket to this years mentoring breakfast, which will be at <time minute="0" hour="8" />8 a.m.</time /> Thursday in the Pegasus Ballroom of the Student Union. The cost for other attendees is $20 per person.<span> </span>Tickets can be reserved at <span><a href="http://www.bfsa-ucf.org/">www.bfsa-ucf.org</a></span>, by contacting <a href="mailto:dpriest@mail.ucf.edu"><span>dpriest@mail.ucf.edu </span></a>or by calling 407-823-2137.</p><p>The program will bring in speakers throughout the year and offer workshops and sessions during which students can develop and practice their leadership skills. Speakers will also offer insight into getting into special fields such as drama, art and science and help students get internships before graduation.</p><p>The programs first guest is professor Daniel Banks from NYUs <place /><placename />Tisch</placename /> <placetype />School</placetype /></place /> of the Arts. Banks will speak at the breakfast and will speak again at <time minute="0" hour="18" />6 p.m.</time /> Thursday in room 260 of the Math and <place /><placename />Physics</placename /> <placetype />Building</placetype /></place />. That presentation is free and open to the public. </p><p>Banks presentations will focus on hip-hop, theatre and the work of Hip Hop Theatre Initiative in Africa. </p><p>For those who want to speak with Banks in a smaller setting, he will hold a lunch discussion from <time minute="0" hour="11" />11 a.m.</time /> to <time minute="0" hour="13" />1 p.m.</time /> Friday, Feb. 16, in the Marketplace. Reservations are encouraged for the luncheon. To make a reservation, or for more information, contact Legacy coordinator Denice Rozier at 407-823-4649 or at <a href="mailto:legacy@mail.ucf.edu">legacy@mail.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

